[ YouTube is owned by Google. LinkedIn is owned by Microsoft, the biggest investor in OpenAI. That ownership map is the whole game.

Last week's Friday SEO Tip covers what I call the big six: the six platforms AI search engines actually pull from when they decide what to cite, recommend, and surface. 

Most local businesses we work with at Boulder SEO Marketing are putting in real effort. Posting, updating, running ads. And they are still invisible when someone asks ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini or Perplexity for a recommendation in their area.

Here's why this matters right now. The gap is almost never that you are doing too little. It is that you are active on the wrong platforms. AI search engines are not pulling from everywhere equally. They pull from a small set of sources that have earned deep trust, and most of that trust traces back to ownership and indexing depth.

The big six:
→ YouTube. Google owns it, so it is the most cited resource in AI results. One short tip a week is fifty-two indexed entries a year. 
→ LinkedIn. Microsoft owns it and funds OpenAI, so what you post here reaches ChatGPT more reliably than almost anywhere else. 
→ Reddit. Nearly every Google search now surfaces a thread. Join the conversations already ranking on page one. 
→ Quora and Medium. Low barrier, deep informational authority. Answer the five questions your customers ask most. 
→ Google Business Profile. The anchor for local AI results. Post updates consistently, not once a month when you remember.

Here's what I've learned in nearly three decades of doing this. You do not need to be everywhere. You need to be in the right places, and you need to show up consistently. 

The businesses already getting cited in AI Overviews and LLMs did not crack a secret algorithm. They picked the right platforms and stayed steady.

Pick one this week. Build the rhythm. Add the next when you are ready. The visibility compounds in a way paid channels never will.

